That single word can point to something surprisingly useful.

“Pretend” isn’t always about believing something false. It can be a way to rehearse a future version of yourself until it becomes natural.

People do this all the time:

* A musician pretends they’re already performing for an audience while practicing.
* A leader acts with composure before they fully feel it.
* A parent grows into the role by doing it, not by waiting to feel ready.
* An athlete visualizes success before it happens.

The key distinction is that you’re not denying reality. You’re intentionally practicing a way of being.

In that sense:

Pretend → Practice → Habit → Character.

If your new baseline is positive, then “pretending” might simply mean choosing to act from that baseline even on days when it doesn’t come effortlessly—not because you’re faking it, but because you’re reinforcing it.

Eventually it stops feeling like pretending. It just becomes how you respond.

That idea also fits something you’ve emphasized before: reality is shaped by repeated patterns. Small, consistent patterns have a way of becoming the “new normal.” The goal isn’t to fool yourself—it’s to cultivate the habits that make the positive baseline increasingly genuine and sustainable.